caption: Delicious food. Super friendly staff. Best bar area for hangout or drinks and the interior design is one of a kind. I can’t wait to have a special dinner in their beautiful dining room again. Great job guys.
Great cold brew!

First time trying them during quarantine as they offered a meal for 2. Rather dissatisfied with the sides I received. The smoked potatoes were still hard (undercooked)  and the beans, I've never had beans of this consistency. The texture was as if they also were undercooked, almost raw but the flavor was fine. The Fried chicken and ribs were fantastic though. The dessert was really good to. But for the price it failed to satisfy.
I ordered the meal for two for carryout and it was fantastic especially for the price. Would highly recommend

(Translated by Google) It is a cozy place to enjoy with family or friends the good service of those who work there  (Original) Es un lugar acogedor para disfrutar en familia o amigos el buen servicio  de los que trabajan hay

I took my daughter to Wherewithall while she was home on Spring break and it was just fabulous. The main dishes the night we went were Hake for the fish and Pork Loin for the meat. The pork was great but the Hake was just out of this world. Perfectly poached (I think) with a tangy but not too strong horseradish sauce. In addition to the four listed courses they brought three "surprise" tastes, a miso broth, trout fritters, and ground venison on greens. All very tasty. Portions were just the right size; you leave satisfied but not feeling like you've overeaten despite 7 or 8 dishes. I will definitely return.

We went to Wherewithall for Valentine’s Day. When we got there, it was clear they were a bit overwhelmed as all of the seatings were behind. We were seated 15 minutes after our initial reservation. That aside, the food was tasty and interesting, but, as some others have said, pricey for what we got. Highlights were the fjord trout (amazing); blue grits and “ham”; the initial “snacks” (one was a fried mashed potato croquette); and the fennel palate cleanser. The dessert, a baked alaska, was good but not amazing. I was disappointed most of all in the duck dish. Despite the flavor profile being great, the fat on the duck was not rendered and it was very tough and chewy, to the point I had to spit some bites out. This just is not up to par with their other food or their sister restaurant, Parachute. We also noticed that we were skipped over for one of the appetizers - some sort of soup. Overall, we think perhaps the Valentine’s Day rush impeded our experience, so left feeling a bit underwhelmed for the price, but we will consider returning on a less busy day.
Food, drink, service, everything was amazing.  Not as selective of a menu as parachute but enjoyed every plate that was served.

Big fan of parachute down the street, went here last night and really, really loved it. Each course was gorgeous and tasty, the cheese plate at the end felt so fun, finished the meal with some plum brandy, and I would absolutely recommend it to a friend. It was a great experience.
Exceptional service and amazing food! Monday night half price wines. Short ribs and lobster mac and cheese;) Great stuff.

Food and service were both excellent. The food is very eclectic, but tasted very good. There is obviously a lot of work that goes into presenting the food before it comes out to the table because none of the food is piping hot.  All presentations were great.
Dinner at the bar was great! The bar snacks were just enough for a light dinner. The bartenders were super friendly and made great recommendations and really well balanced drinks.
drimnks
I absolutely love this place and continue to return to it over and over again Best price for Prix menu. If you go here you'll have an outstanding time It's very good company too.
Fixed menu, which in this case was a curse because at least half the dishes were pretty bad.

The meal was fantastic, with impeccable service and a ton of off-menu snacks. That being said, I cant get over the premium we paid given the food was fantastic but no better than some other of our favorite spots. Given the location, the overhead cant be high, but maybe it's the fact that the meal is paced over 2.5 hours (with no feeling of being rushed). Regardless, will definitely return but only for a super special occasion.

This place is so wonderful and delicious!! I love that in addition to the 4 items listed in the prix fie you end up getting lots of additional small bites!  I do think it’s a little bit pricy but it’s still very delicious.

First important note: menu changes daily, so this was my experience with the $85 NYE menu. Your experience will vary!  Second note: I was initially concerned that the portion sizes were going to be small and we would leave hungry. That was not the case.  4 course prix fixe with several mini courses peppered between meant we were both satisfied.  That being said, before we could order drinks, we had two of these mini courses on our table plus a basket of artisan bread. One of these was hot and losing temp as we figured out what to drink. Each time the courses were delivered, the description was quietly mentioned and that person darted back to the kitchen. While our primary server was great (helpful, detailed and pleasant), they had a lot of tables to cover in a crowded restaurant so we didn’t see them often.  Overall, the service really detracted from the quality of the meal.  Our oysters were tasty but still attached to shell (and we had no utensils) so was hard to eat initially. I had to detach with my finger.  I believe the second mini dish was a Yorkshire pudding (couldn’t hear well) which was a bit eggy. I won’t pretend to be an expert of British cooking, but the eggy bread dough + the light cream cheese spread meant that you really just tasted egg.  The bread itself was amazing. I assume it was baked in house because it tasted like one of those loaves that could support a restaurant of its own like Tartine with a cult following like Nancy Silverton or Peter Reinhart.  Great crust, delicate interior and rich earthy flavor. Unfortunately the individual who was slicing the bread was crushing the crumb as they sliced so it ended up smashed in our bread basket. This may sound like a nitpick (and it is) but if you’re going to go through the trouble of providing fantastic artisan bread, you really should slice it properly.  Bouillabaisse was surprisingly good for me because I’m not big on intense fish flavors.  This was strong but balanced nicely by the pepper and tarragon - I enjoyed it quite a bit.  Celeriac course was nice. Solid presentation and hit the right savory notes.  Black cod marinated in beet juice was my favorite of the night. The fish was incredibly delicate but had a light crust on it so you had some contrasting textures. Portabellas and (I think) chard were also great.  The main course was a wagyu bavette served with some mysterious sauce with celery strands on it. The sauce and celery were great on their own. But I didn’t find that they paired well with the beef. I think the sauce would have paired better with chicken or maybe duck breast because of how sweet it was. The beef wasn’t the star of the show and it should have been. It was a nice tender cut, but had little flavor itself and didn’t fit in that dish with the sweet sauce.  Side note: if you need to explain to each customer how to use the steak knife, it might be time to buy new knives.  We added the daily cheese plate which was a nice assortment of 3 cheeses. The cranberry spread that was served with the crisps was good for palette cleansing between cheeses but didn’t compliment the cheeses itself when combined.  Last, we had 3 separate desserts of varying size that were unique and satisfying. I myself enjoyed all three (hay ice cream, kings cake w/crème fraîche and a one bite tart with some citrus curd), but my wife wasn’t into the more unique flavors (she disliked the ice cream).  Overall, the dishes didn’t land for the two of us. Some (black cod) were enjoyable but there weren’t enough wow moments. The beef was also a big miss for me.  Coupled with the other few pieces and the jarring service, we were a bit disappointed for an all in $350 check (again, NYE, we added a few drinks and the cheese courses).  For that size of check, I expected a more cohesive menu with fewer missteps.  Because it’s a set course, it’s hard to tell your server you didn’t enjoy a dish and ask for something else.  Would try again considering they have something new each night but will wait a bit before returning.

This sister to parachute, is wonderful. Highly recommended. Starting off with the super friendly bar when you walk in we’re waiting for your table feels like a pleasure not a penalty. Environment is casual food is superb. Presentation is excellent flavors are delicious especially at this price point. Would highly recommend it.
Very friendly with a creative and hyper-seasonal menu.

I had my doubts about this place but honestly after today I definitely rate this one of the best restaurants I had in all of Chicago (this includes restaurants in the West Loop as well.) The grain of salt: menu changes every day so it will be hard to tell what to expect. Otherwise flawless
Excellent service and food that somehow exceeded it.
Exceeded our expectations every step of the way! Would highly recommend and we will definitely be back!

This meal was everything you could want in a prix fixe meal. The price included everything shown in the menu plus lots of little extras and surprises between the courses. Everything was delicious and I felt that the meal was worth way more than the menu price of $65. I can’t recommend wherewithall highly enough.

Unbelievable dining experience. Stop reading this and make a reservation. First, the four-course  menu is punctuated with 4-5 snackers, which were all incredibly thoughtful and fun takes on appetizers (frisee dippers with buttermilk dressing, lightly fried shitake with cherry-bomb pepper aioli, a shot of pork ramen broth, etc). The desserts were genuinely moving. The mains were filling and diverse. A few veggies I had never heard of (ice plant?). Even things that felt like afterthoughts - like a palate-cleansing apple cider vin/clove granita in a glass bowl - were revelations. Service was top notch. I want to be friends with everyone working there. Can't say enough good things!
Really good food, amazing service. Definitely a repeat. The meal was on the heavy side though
Great meal!
Really great dinner!  Wer loved it.
I notice that the cooks never have hair nets, my food was touched without gloves, no bread net, yet the prices were outrageous. Don't go there if you are hungry and bring a lot of money.
Courses were simply just salty. No complexity with the flavors. The duck was very tough and chewy. They should offer other dishes for the course menu. 2 stars pretty fair given the exorbitant cost.

Plate after plate after plate. The free courses don't seem to end.  It's an avalanche of Michelin quality invention. What's most noteworthy is the attention to small batch winemakers.  The table bread is rough-hewn and an homage to the Publican's, except the center is even more pillowy and dreamy.  Venison from a dream. Each course inventive, playful, artfully complex and just plain socko. I wept.

Really nice tasting menu with a modest price and lofty aspirations. The space itself is spare but comfortable. They’ve made remarkable use of a relatively small room to provide ample seating without feeling crowded. Service was attentive and rarely left us wanting. The food was a delight, with vegetarian, octopus, and iberico ham collar courses and a baked apple dessert supplemented with 3 small bite warm ups and palette cleansers. While the seafood and ham were perfectly cooked and balanced dishes, I’d reflect that if all veg focused dishes were as perfectly delicious as theirs I’d live a happy vegetarian life. The wine pairings were a surprise as well. At this price point you can’t expect them to lean into the grand crus and rarities of the world. Instead, they found modest wines which you might not always choose to sit and sip alone, but which complimented the food in a way that elevated both. I’ve been to multi Michelin starred places which couldn’t get wine right, but these guys nailed it. A brilliant experience overall.
Staff are awesome!! Shout out to my bartender Nikki.  Just had drinks and bites at the bar but excited to try the dining side next time.
Totally fun concept of not having to choose what to eat. Everything was meticulously prepared and totally delicious.

The same hospitality and creativity we would have expected at Parachute but with a completely different concept and vibe.  The space itself is a great adaptation to the building they were able to access, and the "reveal" of the dining room after passing the host and then kitchen was a cool surprise.  We barely made it in time for final seating yet the entire staff couldn't have been more welcoming and relaxed.  Our meal, punctuated with any number of "gifts" from the kitchen, was inventive and unexpected. And the wine pairings, pitch perfect, was surprising at every turn. Only 7 weeks in and Beverly Kim looks to have another winner.
Ok food. Average given its cost and ratings
The food was great and the atmosphere was upscale but comfortable.
Love the food, small  portions with different  flavors, great service, cozy and  not too crowded.
Every dish was fantastic.

Great experience! Love the idea of not having to choose what I'm going to eat, especially in a restaurant where everything will be delicious! We got drinks at the bar and them promptly sat at our table. Not only did the restaurant confirm our food allergies in a confirmation text they made sure it was still the same at the table. In addition to the four main courses there were smaller sizes dishes in between. Everything was nicely timed and came out hot and delicious. Overall I was really happy with our dinner and will be back for more!

It's a set multi-course for dinner. The menus didn't have our names on them so it took us a minute to realize it, but they tailored the courses/descriptions to our dietary needs/preferences. They texted us two days before the dinner. Very nice touch. Easy communication. The food was inventive and didn't involve a lot of heavy cream or oils. It wasn't too rich. Lots of eat flavors but nothing overwhelming. Everyone was fan.
Enjoyed the experience a great deal.  Entertained a visiting friend and this place makes a short list of places they'd like to visit again.
Deliciously fun food, great service, priced very reasonably.
Chef John Clark and his wife are great people and great cooks. You will enjoy eating and visiting here.
